# Client-Server separation and GUI (Forge 1.20.1)

## Physical Side vs Logical Side

| Side | Meaning |
|------|---------|
| Physical CLIENT | The game process rendering the world |
| Physical SERVER | Dedicated server process (or integrated server in single-player) |
| Logical CLIENT | Code running on the client that can ONLY observe/render |
| Logical SERVER | Code running on the dedicated server that manages world state |

### Rules

- **Never** call client-only code from a logical server context
- **Never** modify server-side world data from the logical client
- Use `@OnlyIn(Dist.CLIENT)` for client-only code
- Use `DistExecutor` for safe side-aware execution without annotations

## DistExecutor

```java
// Run on the CLIENT only
DistExecutor.unsafeRunWhenOn(Dist.CLIENT, () -> MyClass::clientInit);

// Run on the DEDICATED_SERVER only
DistExecutor.unsafeRunWhenOn(Dist.DEDICATED_SERVER, () -> MyClass::serverInit);

// Safe version with supplier (avoids classloading issues on wrong side)
DistExecutor.safeRunWhenOn(Dist.CLIENT, () -> () -> MyClass.clientInit());
```

**Note:** `@OnlyIn` exists but **there is NO reason for using this annotation directly. Use `DistExecutor` or a check on `FMLEnvironment#dist` instead.**

## FMLEnvironment

```java
// Quick side check
if (FMLEnvironment.dist == Dist.CLIENT) {
    // client-only initialization
}

// NEVER use for game logic — only for initialization/setup
```

## GUI System Overview

```
Player interacts
      │
      ▼
Block#use (Server) ──► creates MenuProvider ──► openContainer (Server)
                                                       │
                                                       ▼
                                              ContainerMenu + Screen pair
                                                       │
                                               MenuScreens.register()
                                                       │
                                                       ▼
                                                   Renders Screen
```

## Decision: Container/Menu type

```
IF interactable block with persistent data (machine, chest)
  → AbstractContainerMenu + MenuType + Screen

IF just a simple interaction (no data)
  → Screen directly (without Menu)

IF inventory with multiple slots
  → AbstractContainerMenu (for slot management and quickMoveStack)
```

## MenuType Registration

```java
// 1. Define the Menu class
public class MyMenu extends AbstractContainerMenu {
    public MyMenu(int windowId, Inventory inv, FriendlyByteBuf extraData) {
        super(MY_MENU_TYPE.get(), windowId);
        // slot layout...
    }

    // Shift-click transfer logic
    @Override
    public ItemStack quickMoveStack(Player player, int slotIndex) {
        return ItemStack.EMPTY; // or implement slot transfer
    }

    @Override
    public boolean stillValid(Player player) {
        return true;
    }
}

// 2. Register MenuType
public static final DeferredRegister<MenuType<?>> MENUS =
    DeferredRegister.create(ForgeRegistries.MENU_TYPES, MOD_ID);

public static final RegistryObject<MenuType<MyMenu>> MY_MENU =
    MENUS.register("my_menu",
        () -> IContainerFactory.of(MyMenu::new)
    );
```

## Screen registration (CLIENT ONLY)

```java
@Mod.EventBusSubscriber(modid = MOD_ID, value = Dist.CLIENT)
public class ClientSetup {
    @SubscribeEvent
    public static void init(FMLClientSetupEvent event) {
        MenuScreens.register(MyMenuTypes.MY_MENU.get(), MyScreen::new);
    }
}
```

## Data Synchronization (ContainerData)

```java
// Define synced data
private final ContainerData dataSlots = new ContainerData() {
    @Override public int get(int index) { return /* ... */; }
    @Override public void set(int index, int value) { /* ... */; }
    @Override public int getCount() { return 1; }
};

// In Menu constructor
super(menuType, windowId, inventory, extraData, dataSlots);

// Set from server
menu.dataSlots.set(0, newValue); // Triggers sync to client automatically

// Read on client in Screen
int value = menu.dataSlots.get(0);
```

## Block → Menu binding

```java
public class MyBlock extends Block {
    @Override
    public InteractionResult use(BlockState state, Level level, BlockPos pos,
            Player player, InteractionHand hand, BlockHitResult result) {
        if (!level.isClientSide) {
            MenuProvider menuProvider = state.getMenuProvider(level, pos);
            if (menuProvider != null) {
                level.playSound(null, pos, SoundEvents.UI_BUTTON_CLICK.value(),
                    SoundSource.BLOCKS, 0.5f, 0.8f);
                player.openMenu(menuProvider);
            }
        }
        return InteractionResult.sidedSuccess(level.isClientSide);
    }

    @Override
    public MenuProvider getMenuProvider(BlockState state, Level level,
            BlockPos pos) {
        return new SimpleMenuProvider(
            (windowId, inv, player) -> new MyMenu(windowId, inv, InvMenu.noGlobalStd()), // wrong
            Component.literal("My Menu")
        );
        // Better: use IContainerFactory with the registered MenuType
        return new MenuProvider() {
            @Override public Component getDisplayName() {
                return Component.literal("My Menu");
            }
            @Override public AbstractContainerMenu createMenu(int windowId,
                    Inventory inv, Player player) {
                return new MyMenu(windowId, inv, player);
            }
        };
    }
}
```

## Common errors

- ❌ Opening a Menu on the server without a registered `MenuType` → crash
- ❌ `MenuScreens.register()` called on server → `FMLClientSetupEvent` already prevents this, but guard with `@OnlyIn(Dist.CLIENT)`
- ❌ `quickMoveStack` not implemented → Shift-click does nothing
- ❌ Modifying world state in `AbstractContainerMenu` constructor → too early, use `broadcastChanges()`
- ❌ `ContainerData` set from client → must be set server-side only
